Welcome to notebook five of the Java track. The topic for this session is the boring but essential side of any real program. Errors, files, and input output. The Stream application programming interface and lambdas we covered in notebook four are how you express your logic. Exceptions and input output are how that logic talks to the outside world, without becoming a debugging nightmare when things inevitably go wrong.

Here is the map for what we will cover. First, why Java has exceptions and where they fit in the language. The Throwable hierarchy, with its two branches, Error and Exception, and the special subtype Runtime Exception. The crucial distinction between checked and unchecked exceptions, and the rule the compiler enforces on the checked side. The try, catch, and finally syntax, and how control flow moves through it. Multi catch, which lets one catch block handle several exception types. How to throw an exception explicitly. How to write your own custom exception types. Exception chaining, which preserves the original cause when you wrap one exception inside another. The try with resources statement, which is Java's solution to safe cleanup of file handles, connections, and any other Auto Closeable resource. The Path type from the new input output package, which is the modern replacement for the old File class. The Files utility, with its high level methods for reading, writing, copying, listing, and walking. And finally, a brief note on serialization, with the strong recommendation to prefer modern formats like JSON for any new code.

Let us start with the question, why does Java have exceptions at all. Things go wrong in real programs. A file does not exist. The network drops. A user supplies a string where you expected a number. A database connection times out. Java's answer to all of these situations is the exception mechanism. An exception is a value that propagates up the call stack until something catches it, abandoning the normal return path along the way.

The alternative to exceptions is to return a special sentinel value from the failing method. Minus one means failure. Null means missing. Zero means error. The problem with sentinels is that they quietly force every caller to remember to check. If you forget the check, the bad value just flows through your program and corrupts something downstream. Exceptions invert this default. You opt out of failure handling by letting the exception propagate naturally up to a caller who is prepared to deal with it. You opt in to failure handling by catching the exception in a try block.

Every exception in Java extends the class Throwable. Throwable has two big branches. The first branch is Error. An Error is a fatal java virtual machine level problem. Out of memory error. Stack overflow error. You do not catch these. You cannot meaningfully recover from them. The second branch is Exception. Exception itself, and most of its subclasses, are recoverable conditions that application code might reasonably handle.

Inside Exception, there is one specially marked subtree. Runtime Exception, and all its descendants. The runtime exception subtree gets special treatment from the compiler. Everything outside it, but still inside Exception, is what we call a checked exception. Everything inside Runtime Exception is unchecked.

Now the crucial rule. Java is one of the few languages with checked exceptions. A checked exception is a compile time contract that says, this method might throw an io exception, and you must either catch it, or declare on your own method signature that you let it propagate. The keyword for the declaration is throws, written at the end of the method signature, followed by the exception type. If you do not handle a checked exception in one of those two ways, the code does not compile.

The rule of thumb the language designers gave was, use checked exceptions for recoverable conditions that a caller might reasonably handle. A file might not exist. A network call might fail. Use unchecked exceptions for programmer mistakes. You passed a negative size. You dereferenced a null. In practice, modern Java code leans unchecked. Checked exceptions do not compose well with lambdas and streams, because the abstract method on Function and Predicate and Consumer does not declare any checked exception. So if your lambda body would throw a checked exception, you have to catch it inside the lambda or wrap it. Most modern libraries lean toward unchecked, and you should too in new code.

The try, catch, finally statement is the construct that handles exceptions. The try block wraps the code that might throw. Each catch block handles a specific exception type. The optional finally block runs no matter what. Exception or not, return or not. The finally block is the classic place to release a resource, although try with resources, which we will see in a moment, is the modern replacement for that pattern.

Order matters in catch blocks. The java virtual machine picks the first catch block whose declared type matches the thrown exception. If you write catch of Exception before catch of Number Format Exception, the more specific block would never run, because every Number Format Exception is also an Exception. The compiler will reject this ordering. Always go from most specific to most general.

Multi catch lets you handle several exception types in one catch block, when the handling logic is the same for all of them. The syntax is catch, open paren, type one, vertical bar, type two, close paren, the variable name, then the body. The vertical bar separator means or. The variable inside the catch block has the closest common supertype, so you can only call methods that exist on that supertype.

A common mistake worth flagging now. Avoid catching the bare Exception type just to make code compile. That swallows real bugs alongside the failure you meant to handle. Catch the specific type you are prepared to recover from, and let the rest propagate up to a higher level where someone is.

To raise an exception explicitly, use the throw keyword. The expression after throw must be a Throwable instance, almost always one you construct with new. The Java standard library gives you several ready made unchecked exception types that cover most cases. Reach for Illegal Argument Exception when the caller passed a value outside what the method accepts. Reach for Illegal State Exception when the method is called on an object that is not in a state to handle the call. Reach for Null Pointer Exception when a required reference is null. There is a helper called Objects dot require Non Null that throws Null Pointer Exception with a clean message. Reach for Unsupported Operation Exception when the operation is not supported on this implementation, like calling add on an immutable list.

When none of the standard exception types communicates enough, write your own. The convention is to extend Runtime Exception for an unchecked exception, or to extend Exception for a checked one. Provide constructors that accept a message string and an optional cause. The cause is another throwable that explains why this exception was raised.

For a domain example, an Insufficient Funds Exception might extend Runtime Exception, hold the requested amount and the available balance as fields, and produce a clean error message in the super call. Throwing it gives you a domain specific signal that any layer in the stack can catch. The fields let the caller introspect the exception programmatically, not just read its message.

When you catch one exception and throw another, you should pass the original as the cause. This preserves the full chain in the stack trace, which is invaluable for debugging. The pattern is, catch the lower level exception, like io exception, then throw a higher level domain exception with super of message comma cause. When you later log the chained exception, the stack trace shows both layers. You see the application level meaning. You also see the original root cause, printed under Caused by. This is the difference between a useful production log and a useless one.

Now we come to one of Java's most important small features. Try with resources. Before Java seven, releasing a resource like a file handle, an input stream, or a database connection, required a try finally dance with a null check inside. The pattern was long, easy to get wrong, and silently broken when the close call itself threw.

Try with resources, introduced in Java seven, makes resource cleanup a one liner. Any class that implements the Auto Closeable interface can go in parentheses after the try keyword. The java virtual machine guarantees that the resource's close method is called when the block exits, whether by normal completion, an explicit return, or an exception. Multiple resources can be declared in the same try, separated by semicolons. They close in reverse declaration order, just like local variables would clean up in reverse construction order.

The Auto Closeable interface has a single method called close. Any class you write can implement it whenever it holds something that needs cleanup. A database connection. A file handle. A network socket. Once you implement Auto Closeable, your class slots seamlessly into try with resources blocks. The pattern is so common that modern Java code rarely uses a hand written finally for cleanup anymore.

Now we shift to filesystem input output. The Path type, in the package java nio file, is the modern replacement for the old File class. A Path is an immutable abstract representation of a filesystem path. Important. It does not mean the path exists on disk. It is just the name of a location. Construction is via the static factory Path dot of, which takes either a full path string, or several string components that get joined with the platform separator.

Once you have a Path, you can ask pure questions about it without touching the disk. The get File Name method returns the last segment. The get Parent method returns everything before the last segment. The get Root method returns the root, like the forward slash on unix. The is Absolute method tells you whether the path is absolute or relative. The resolve method joins a Path with another component, treating it as a child. The relativize method computes the relative path from one Path to another. None of these methods touch the filesystem.

The Files utility class, also in java nio file, is your one stop shop for actual filesystem input output. It operates on Path values. The high level methods cover ninety percent of real use. The exists method checks whether the path exists on disk. The is Directory method checks whether it is a directory. The size method returns the file size in bytes. The get Last Modified Time method returns the modification timestamp.

For reading text files, the read String method returns the whole file as a string. The read All Lines method returns a list of strings, one per line. For writing text, the write String method takes a Path and a string, and either creates or truncates the file. The write method with a list of strings writes each on its own line.

For huge files, do not use read String or read All Lines, because they load everything into memory at once. Use the lines method instead, which returns a Stream of strings, lazily. The stream pulls one line at a time. Wrap the call in try with resources, because the stream holds an open file handle that needs to be closed.

For binary files, the read All Bytes method returns the file contents as a byte array. The write method with a byte array writes the bytes back out. Both methods are appropriate for small to medium binary files. For huge binary files, use the lower level new Input Stream and new Output Stream methods, which give you streaming access without loading everything at once.

Directory operations follow the same shape. The create Directories method creates a directory and any missing parents, like the unix command mkdir minus p. The create Directory method creates a single directory and fails if it already exists, or if a parent is missing.

To list the contents of a directory at one level, call Files dot list. This returns a Stream of Paths for the immediate children. Wrap it in try with resources, because the stream holds the directory handle open. To walk a directory tree recursively, call Files dot walk. This returns a Stream of every Path in the tree, depth first. To search a tree for files matching some condition, call Files dot find with a maximum depth and a bi predicate that takes the Path and its attributes and returns a boolean. Find is essentially walk plus filter, optimised so the predicate runs during traversal.

For copying and moving, the copy method takes a source Path, a destination Path, and optional copy options like Standard Copy Option dot Replace Existing. The move method has the same signature. Both throw if the source does not exist, or if the destination exists and you did not pass Replace Existing.

For deletion, the delete method removes a Path, and throws if the path does not exist. The delete If Exists method is the safe variant. It returns a boolean indicating whether something was actually deleted.

One critical reminder. Every Stream returned by Files dot list, Files dot walk, Files dot find, and Files dot lines holds an open file handle underneath. Always wrap them in try with resources. Otherwise you leak file descriptors, and on long running processes, this is the kind of slow leak that takes down production servers in the middle of the night.

The last topic for this notebook is serialization. Java's built in serialization mechanism turns an object graph into bytes you can write to a file, or send over a socket, and then restore back into objects. The mechanism is opt in via the Serializable marker interface. A marker interface is one with no methods. You just declare implements Serializable, and your class is eligible for serialization.

There are a few details. Every Serializable class should declare a static final long called serial Version UID. This is a version number that the runtime uses to detect when the class has changed in a way that breaks compatibility with serialized data. The transient keyword marks fields that should be skipped during serialization, for fields like passwords or cached values that should not be persisted. The write Object and read Object methods on Object Output Stream and Object Input Stream do the actual work.

Now the warning, not the recommendation. Java's built in serialization is convenient, but it has serious problems. It has been a recurring source of security vulnerabilities, because deserializing untrusted data can execute arbitrary code. It tightly couples your class structure to its wire format, which makes refactoring painful. And the java development kit team is actively working to replace it.

For real persistence and inter service communication, prefer a structured format. JSON, using libraries like Jackson or Gson. YAML for configuration. Protocol Buffers or Avro for high performance binary serialization. We will use Jackson extensively once we reach Spring, where every rest controller maps to JSON automatically. Treat Serializable as legacy knowledge. You need to recognise it in old code, but you should rarely add it to new code.

That wraps notebook five. You can now handle failure in a way that callers can reason about, manage file handles safely with try with resources, and read or write any text or binary file with Files and Path. These are the boring foundations that every real Java service is built on. Spring services in particular lean on try with resources for database connections, for transactions, and for any other resource that has to be released. The pattern you learned here will reappear in every Spring chapter ahead.

Notebook six turns to concurrency. We will look at threads. The executor service framework, which hides raw thread management. The brand new virtual threads, introduced in Java twenty one, which make a million concurrent tasks cheap. The completable future type, for composing asynchronous work. And a tour of the java util concurrent utilities, including locks, atomic variables, and the concurrent collections.
